docs.lead_paragraph: On June 2, as Black Lives Matter protesters swarmed America’s streets demanding an end to the racist vestiges of America’s troubled past, a teenager from a San Diego suburb posted eight words on Twitter that would soon ignite a less visible, though perhaps just as powerful, movement.

headline.main: Black Lives Matter Protests Spawn Push for Athletes to Attend Historically Black Colleges
headline.print_headline: For Some Athletes, History Becomes New Again

docs.abstract: An open letter published by Harper’s, signed by luminaries including Margaret Atwood and Wynton Marsalis, argued for openness to “opposing views.” The debate began immediately.
docs.snippet: An open letter published by Harper’s, signed by luminaries including Margaret Atwood and Wynton Marsalis, argued for openness to “opposing views.” The debate began immediately.
docs.lead_paragraph: The killing of George Floyd has brought an intense moment of racial reckoning in the United States. As protests spread across the country, they have been accompanied by open letters calling for — and promising — change at white-dominated institutions across the arts and academia.

headline.main: Artists and Writers Warn of an ‘Intolerant Climate.’ Reaction Is Swift.
headline.print_headline: In a Letter, Artists and Scholars Warn of an ‘Intolerant Climate’

byline.original: By Jennifer Schuessler and Elizabeth A. Harris

docs.abstract: A recent number of pro-police rallies have led to fights and arrests as civilian New Yorkers turn on one another over their view of the N.Y.P.D.
docs.snippet: A recent number of pro-police rallies have led to fights and arrests as civilian New Yorkers turn on one another over their view of the N.Y.P.D.
docs.lead_paragraph: Clashes between protesters and the police were familiar sights in the days after the death of George Floyd under the knee of a police officer. But a new kind of unrest has emerged in recent days: confrontations between New Yorkers who support law enforcement and those who are pressing for an overhaul of the Police Department.

headline.main: ‘Blue Lives Matter’ and ‘Defund the Police’ Clash in the Streets
headline.print_headline: Police Supporters Enter Mix of New York’s Street Protests

byline.original: By Juliana Kim and Michael Wilson

docs.abstract: The statue of Jen Reid, a Black Lives Matter protester, was raised on Wednesday in place of a toppled memorial to the slave trader Edward Colston.
docs.snippet: The statue of Jen Reid, a Black Lives Matter protester, was raised on Wednesday in place of a toppled memorial to the slave trader Edward Colston.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Jen Reid, the Black Lives Matter protester whose statue was erected in place of a toppled slave trader in Bristol, England, on Wednesday, said just before the unauthorized installation that she did not know whether the city’s authorities would let it stand there for a few months or a single day.

headline.main: Bristol Removes Statue of Black Protester After Just One Day
headline.print_headline: Black British Protester’s Statue Has Just One Day in the Sun

docs.abstract: In a small Washington town where people of color say they have faced discrimination, activists ran into trouble for drawing “Black Lives Matter” in the streets. Then their white neighbors came to their defense.
docs.snippet: In a small Washington town where people of color say they have faced discrimination, activists ran into trouble for drawing “Black Lives Matter” in the streets. Then their white neighbors came to their defense.
docs.lead_paragraph: SELAH, Wash. — First came the warning: A police officer in the small city of Selah, Wash., told a group of young people that if they continued drawing “Black Lives Matter” chalk art on the sidewalk in front of City Hall, they would be charged with a crime.

headline.main: Seeing ‘Black Lives Matter’ Written in Chalk, One City Declares It a Crime
headline.print_headline: They Have Chalk and a Message. Officials Have One, Too.

docs.abstract: If the league wants to show its commitment to its players, it should hire and promote more Black coaches and executives.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In response to the Black Lives Matter protests, the N.F.L. has decided to play “Lift Every Voice and Sing,” known as the Black national anthem, in Week 1 of its coming season.

headline.main: I Played in the N.F.L. It Needs Way More Than a Black Anthem.
headline.print_headline: The N.F.L.  Needs More  Than a Song

docs.lead_paragraph: CATSKILL, N.Y. — The street painting would stretch about three blocks, from Village Pizza II to the stoplight at the southern end of Main Street, spelling out “Black Lives Matter” on the pavement.

headline.main: ‘A Slap in the Face’: N.Y. Town Rejects Black Lives Matter Painting
headline.print_headline: A Village Divides Over Black Lives Matter Art

docs.abstract: The footage was made available by appointment at a court in Minneapolis, and shows officers seemingly more concerned with controlling George Floyd’s body than saving his life.
docs.snippet: The footage was made available by appointment at a court in Minneapolis, and shows officers seemingly more concerned with controlling George Floyd’s body than saving his life.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Almost from the moment George Floyd encountered the police on May 25, with a gun pointed at him, he appeared terrified and emotionally distraught, according to police camera footage that was newly made available for viewing Wednesday at a courthouse in downtown Minneapolis.

headline.main: Footage of Police Body Cameras Offers Devastating Account of Floyd Killing
headline.print_headline: Body Camera Video Provides a Devastating Account of the Floyd Killing

docs.abstract: The public art project is the latest battle in a feud between President Trump and Mayor Bill de Blasio.
docs.snippet: The public art project is the latest battle in a feud between President Trump and Mayor Bill de Blasio.
docs.lead_paragraph: New York City painted “Black Lives Matter” in large yellow letters on the street outside Trump Tower on Thursday, the latest flare-up in a yearslong feud between President Trump, who rose to fame as a Manhattan real estate developer, and Mayor Bill de Blasio, who once sought to replace him.

headline.main: N.Y.C. Paints ‘Black Lives Matter’ in Front of Trump Tower
headline.print_headline: Using Broad Strokes, De Blasio Has Words For an Old Adversary

byline.original: By Michael Gold and Daniel E. Slotnik

docs.abstract: After a protest, two Brooklyn lawyers are each facing 45 years behind bars.
docs.snippet: After a protest, two Brooklyn lawyers are each facing 45 years behind bars.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the early morning hours of May 30, Colinford Mattis and Urooj Rahman were arrested in Brooklyn after a night of citywide protests in response to the killing of George Floyd. They are charged with throwing a Molotov cocktail through the broken window of an unoccupied police car. No one was hurt. Both have plead not guilty, but if they are convicted of the array of federal charges leveled against them, there will be no judging involved when they are sentenced: They will face mandatory sentences of 45 years in prison.
